'''Ion (John) William Croitoru''' (born December 7, 1965)<ref name=slam/> is a [[Canada|Canadian]] former [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] of [[Romania]]n descent. He was born and raised in [[Ontario]], Canada. To wrestling fans, Croitoru is better known by his [[ring name]]s, Johnny K-9 and Bruiser Bedlam. He competed in several Canadian wrestling promotions, including [[Stampede Wrestling]], and later wrestled for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]], [[Smoky Mountain Wrestling]], and the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF). He wrestled as a [[Job (professional wrestling)|jobber]] in the WWF, but he was [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#B|booked]] to win titles in several other promotions.

Croitoru is also famous for his history of legal problems. He was a member of Satan's Choice, a [[Motorcycle club|biker gang]], and has also been convicted of [[assault]], [[Smuggling|trafficking]] [[cocaine]] and [[bomb]]ing a police station. In 2005, Croitoru was arrested for the [[murder]] of lawyer Lynn Gilbank and her husband Fred. After a lengthy investigation, the charges were dropped in June 2006 because of insufficient evidence. He worked as a security guard in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]] until being arrested in May 2009 for conspiracy to commit murder. On January 24, 2011, Croitoru was charged with first degree murder in connection with the 2008 execution of Jonathan Barber in [[Burnaby]], British Columbia..

==Wrestling career==
===Early years===
Croitoru trained with Nick DeCarlo and Vic Rossitini before debuting in [[Stampede Wrestling]] in 1984.<ref name=slam/><ref name=cage/> [[Bruce Hart (wrestler)|Bruce Hart]] gave Croitoru the [[ring name]] Orhan Turgedan, The Terrible Turk, a name Croitoru only wrestled under for a short time after leaving the promotion.<ref name=slam/> He continued to wrestle in Canadian [[Independent circuit|independent promotions]], such as [[Grand Prix Wrestling]] in the [[Maritimes]] and Superstars of Wrestling in [[Windsor, Ontario]].<ref name=slam/>

In 1985 Croitoru wrestled for the [[American Wrestling Association]] (AWA), where he received a [[Push (professional wrestling)|push]] and was given a reign as [[Memphis Wrestling Southern Heavyweight Championship|AWA Southern Heavyweight champion]]. He defeated [[Jerry Lawler]] to win the belt on August 16, but [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Drop|dropped]] it back to Lawler in a rematch on September 6.<ref name=awa/> The following month, Croitoru joined the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) as Johnny K-9, where he competed until 1989. Croitoru claims that he decided on this name while being arrested after a fight. He saw "K-9" written on a [[paddywagon]] and decided on the ring name.<ref name=slam/> He worked as a [[Job (professional wrestling)|jobber to the stars]], [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Put over|putting over]] such wrestlers as [[Pedro Morales]], [[Tito Santana]] and [[Paul Orndorff]].<ref name=wwf85>{{cite web|title=Ring Results: 1985|work=The History of WWE|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/85.htm|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref><ref name=wwf86>{{cite web|title=Ring Results: 1986|work=The History of WWE|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/86.htm|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref><ref name=wwf87>{{cite web|title=Ring Results: 1987|work=The History of WWE|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/87.htm|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref><ref name=wwf88>{{cite web|title=Ring Results: 1988|work=The History of WWE|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/88.htm|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref> He wrestled in many [[tag team]] matches and formed a short-lived team with [[Barry Orton|Barry O]] in 1986,<ref name=wwf86/> but his biggest match in the WWF was a televised match against [[Hulk Hogan]].<ref name=oww/> After leaving the WWF, he wrestled on a tour of Japan for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]];<ref name=slam/> he later returned to Japan to compete for [[Frontier Martial-Arts Wrestling]] and [[WAR (wrestling promotion)|Wrestle Association R]].<ref name=slam/> In the late 1980s, Croitoru also worked as a [[Promoter (entertainment)|promoter]] along with Mike Kelly and Bob Clarke, operating the short-lived Canadian International Championship Wrestling in [[Hamilton, Ontario]].<ref name=slam/><ref name=oww/>

===Smoky Mountain Wrestling===
Croitoru joined [[Smoky Mountain Wrestling]] (SMW) in 1994, where he was given the ring name Bruiser Bedlam. According to the storyline, he was brought in by [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]] [[Jim Cornette]] to help settle Cornette's [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[Bob Armstrong]].<ref name=smw14>{{cite web|title=Regional Territories: Smoky Mountain Wrestling #14|url=http://www.kayfabememories.com/Regions/smw/smw14.htm|accessdate=2008-02-18|work=Kayfabe Memories}}</ref> Bedlam and Cornette combined for a victory in a two-on-one [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap match]] over Armstrong at SMW's Blue Grass Brawl II show on April 1.<ref name=pwhb/> That year, he wrestled many [[tag team]] and six-man matches while teaming with Cornette.<ref name=pwhc/><ref name=pwhd>{{cite web|title=Smoky Mountain Wrestling: October<U+2013>December 1994|work=Pro Wrestling History|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/smw/results/1994d.html|accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref>

Bedlam was booked for one title reign with the [[SMW Beat the Champ Television Championship]] during his stint in SMW. The [[kayfabe]] rules behind the title state that any wrestler winning five consecutive matches as champion would win $5,000 but be forced to vacate the title.<ref name=titlehistory>{{cite book|last=Duncan|first=Royal|coauthors=Gary Will|title=Wrestling Title Histories|publisher=Archeus Communications|year=2006|isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref> He won a match against Mike Furnas on April 4, 1994 to win the title, and he defended it over the following month.<ref name=beat/> Bedlam won his fifth match on May 2 with a victory over [[Anthony Michaels]], and the storyline saw him forced to give up the title.<ref name=pwhb>{{cite web|title=Smoky Mountain Wrestling: April<U+2013>June 1994|work=Pro Wrestling History|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/smw/results/1994b.html|accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref> He went on to feud with [[Tracy Smothers]], and the two wrestled in a lengthy series of matches, including several [[Professional wrestling match types#(Object) on a Pole match|Coalminer's glove matches]], in which a glove is available for the wrestlers to use as a weapon.<ref name=pwhb/> Later that year, Bedlam wrestled several matches against "Dirty White Boy" [[Tony Anthony]]. The series consisted of several [[Professional wrestling match types#Cages|steel cage matches]] in which Bedlam put Anthony over.<ref name=pwhc>{{cite web|title=Smoky Mountain Wrestling: July<U+2013>September 1994|work=Pro Wrestling History|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/smw/results/1994c.html|accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref>

===Later career===
In 1994, Croitoru also began wrestling in Midwest Territorial Wrestling, an independent promotion based in Michigan. He took on the ring name Taras Bulba and proclaimed himself "King of [[Professional wrestling match types#Names and variations|Chain matches]]".<ref name=oww/> He competed in a tournament to determine the promotion's first heavyweight champion, but [[Al Snow]] defeated him in the final round.<ref name=mtw/> Bulba was pushed for a run with the belt, however, defeating Mickey Doyle on January 21, 1995 to win the vacant title.<ref name=mtw/> He held the championship for almost four months before dropping it to [[Marty Jannetty]].<ref name=mtw/>

As Johnny K-9, Croitoru returned to the WWF for one match when he was [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Put over|put over]] Gary Scott on January 23, 1995.<ref name=wwf95>{{cite web|title=Ring Results: 1995|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/95.htm|work=The History of WWE|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref> He then competed briefly in Cleveland All Pro Wrestling, where he wrestled against [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]] in a booked loss on March 23.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland All Pro Wrestling|work=Online World of Wrestling|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/capw/|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref> Croitoru also wrestled in [[Border City Wrestling]] (BCW) and was pushed to win the [[BCW Can-Am Heavyweight Championship]] by defeating [[Scott D'Amore]] on May 21, 1995.<ref name=bcw/> He held the title for a little over a month before dropping it back to D'Amore.<ref name=bcw/>

Once again using the ring name Bruiser Beldam, he wrestled for Insane Championship Wrestling (ICW) for a short time in 1996. While there, he competed in a barbed wire baseball bat match against [[Ian Rotten]]; Bedlam was booked for the victory in the match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Insane Championship Wrestling: August 11, 1996|work=Pro Wrestling History|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/mwcw-icw/mwcwcards.html#081196|accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref> He also wrestled [[New Jack]] at ICW's Holiday Hell supercard in a match that ended in a [[Professional wrestling#Countout|double countout]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Holiday Hell|work=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=2008-02-18|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/mwcw-icw/mwcwcards.html#082596}}</ref> He wrestled on [[World Championship Wrestling]]'s first annual [[Ilio DiPaolo]] tribute show, teaming with Cowboy Johnson in a loss to [[Antonio Pugliese|Tony Parisi]] and [[Dominic DeNucci]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WCW Ring Results: 1996|work=The History of WWE|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/wcw96.htm|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref> In the late 1990s, Croitoru wrestled in [[Cambridge, Ontario]]-based International Championship Wrestling. He feuded with [[Greg Valentine]], and the two wrestled in a series of matches. Bedlam won the ICW Heavyweight Championship from Valentine and used [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] tactics such as [[brass knuckles]] to defend the belt.<ref name=oww/><ref>{{cite web|title=Valentine still "hammering" away|work=SLAM! Wrestling|url=http://www.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingArchive/dec8_valentine.html|accessdate=2008-02-22|last=Powell|first=John}}</ref>

Croitoru has also trained several wrestlers, including Pure Wrestling Association's Eddie Osbourne and [[Melissa Maughn]], who competes under the ring name 21st Century Fox.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singles Wrestlers|work=Great Lakes Championship Wrestling|url=http://glcwrestling.sphosting.com/roster.htm|accessdate=2008-02-22|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080630101051/http://glcwrestling.sphosting.com/roster.htm |archivedate = June 30, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Women Wrestler Profiles: 21st Century Fox|work=Online World of Wrestling|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/a/21st-century-fox.html|accessdate=2008-02-22}}</ref>

==Legal trouble==
===Satan's Choice motorcycle gang===
Croitoru has a history of run-ins with the police. Many of his legals problems came while he was president of the [[Hamilton, Ontario]] chapter of the Satan's Choice [[Motorcycle club|motorcycle gang]].<ref name=new/> He was arrested for [[Smuggling|trafficking]] [[cocaine]] and served ten months in prison.<ref name=slam/><ref name=head>{{cite book|isbn=1-59858-324-7|pages=505|title=Headless Man in Topless Bar: Studies of 725 Cases of Strip Club Related Criminal Homicides|last=Kelvin|first=T.A.|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|year=2007}}</ref> Soon after, he was convicted of [[assault]] and was given a sentence of seven months.<ref name=slam/> He encountered more problems on December 15, 1996 when he and several friends from Satan's Choice were kicked out of a [[strip club]] for wearing their gang's [[Gang#Signs|colors]].<ref name=head/> To get revenge, Croitoru and his friends planned to blow up the strip club. They changed their minds, however, and decided to bomb the local police station instead.<ref name=head/> The bomb caused $133,000 in damages to the [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]], [[Ontario]] police station and a nearby bank and injured a police officer.<ref name=street>{{cite web|title=Bruiser Bedlam arrested on street|work=SLAM! Wrestling|last=Dunphy|first=Bill|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingArchive/jan14_bedlam.html|accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref> Croitoru and two friends were arrested and charged, but the trial did not begin until almost two years later.<ref name=bomb>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/15/15904.htm|title=Explosion au quartier g<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>ral des policiers|language=French|accessdate=2008-02-18|work=Radio Canada|date=September 16, 1998}}</ref>

While Croitoru was awaiting trial for the bombing, the Hamilton branch of Satan's Choice was shut down after an [[informant]] gave the police information about the gang's involvement with drug dealing and [[extortion]].<ref name=head/> The gang's clubhouse was confiscated and the club's national leadership decided to disband the Hamilton chapter.<ref name=street/> Croitoru got in a fight in Hamilton with another former Satan's Choice member on January 13, 1998. A police officer saw Croitoru punch the other man in the face and arrested Croitoru for assault.<ref name=street/> In addition to the assault change, Croitoru was charged with extortion from an unrelated incident as well as carrying a concealed weapon and breaking the conditions of his release following the police station bombing.<ref name=street/><ref name=mike>{{cite web|title=Wrestlers in Jail for the Holidays|work=The Wrestling Gospel|url=http://www.mikemooneyham.com/pages/viewfull.cfm?ObjectID=4438C534-3048-826A-C4A8E390AFC75CC9|archivedate=2008-04-17|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080417222656/http://www.mikemooneyham.com/pages/viewfull.cfm?ObjectID=4438C534-3048-826A-C4A8E390AFC75CC9|last=Mooneyham|first=Mike|date=2005-12-18|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref> In September 1998, Croitoru was brought to trial for his role in the bombing.<ref name=bomb/> He was convicted and sentenced to 33 months in prison.<ref name=head/>

Hitman Ken Murdock, who was himself jailed in 1999, has claimed he was hired by the mafia to kill Croitoru but instead chose to spare his life.<ref name="hitcode">{{cite news|last=|Edwards|first=Peter|title=Mafia hitman reveals his code for killings|date=August 13, 2010|publisher=The [[Toronto Star]]|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/ontario/article/847964--mafia-hitman-reveals-his-code-for-killings?bn=1}}</ref>

===Murder accusations===
Croitoru's most famous encounter with the law occurred on January 6, 2005 when he was charged with the November 16, 1998 murders of Lynn and Fred Gilbank.<ref name=held>{{cite web|date=2005-01-07|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2005/01/07/824236.html|accessdate=2008-02-18|title=Johnny K-9 held in double slaying|work=SLAM! Wrestling}}</ref> The couple was shot [[Execution-style murder|execution-style]] with a shotgun.<ref name=ccvf>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccvf.net/index.cfm?viewID=47|title=Gilbanks say it's corruption|date=March 10, 2007|work=Canadian Crime Victim Foundation|last=Clairmont|first=Susan|publisher=Hamilton Spectator|accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref> Police suspect that the murders were in response to Lynn Gilbank's assistance in getting William and Angie Smith into a [[witness protection]] program after William Smith gave the police information about the Gravelle crime family.<ref name=file>{{cite web|title=The Police File on the Gravelle Family|work=Media Awareness Project|url=http://www.mapinc.org/drugnews/v06/n108/a04.html?176|accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref> Croitoru, who had several contacts within the Gravelle family (including a contract to kill police inspector Rick Wills, who was investigating the Gravelles),<ref>{{cite web|title=From top cop ... to $20,000 bail|work=Hamilton Spectator|first=Susan|last=Clairmont|date=2009-05-15|accessdate=2009-05-15|url=http://www.thespec.com/News/Local/article/566577}}</ref> was a suspect in the investigation and had his phones [[Telephone tapping|tapped]] during the investigation.<ref name=ctv>{{cite web|title=A Tale of Two Families|last=Mitchell|first=Brett|date=March 10, 2007|work=CTV|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070309/wfive_twofamilies_070310/20070310?hub=WFive|accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref>

After an investigation that lasted six years and cost $6 million, police laid charges against Croitoru and Andre Gravelle.<ref name=ctv/> Croitoru was charged with two counts of [[Murder#First and second degree|first degree murder]] and two counts of [[Conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] to commit murder.<ref name=new/> After spending seven months in prison, Croitoru was released on $100,000 [[bail]].<ref name=bail/> He was arrested on December 2, 2005 for violating his bail terms, and police filed another extortion charge against him.<ref name=mike/>

Evidence against Croitoru and Gravelle was presented over the course of eight weeks in 2006, but the judge stated that the case against the two accused was not strong.<ref name=lawsuit/> [[Attorney General of Ontario|Ontario Attorney General]] [[Michael Bryant (politician)|Michael Bryant]] withdrew the charges on June 12, 2006.<ref name=path>{{cite web|title=A complicated path|url=http://www.thespec.com/article/200676|work=Hamilton Spectator|date=May 25, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-21}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Following this action by the attorney general, both Croitoru and Andre Gravelle announced plans to file lawsuits against people involved with the prosecution. Gravelle is suing for $25 million, and Croitoru is seeking $15 million for wrongful imprisonment and [[malicious prosecution]].<ref name=new/><ref name=lawsuit>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalpost.com/news/story.html?id=e18a1d29-adc3-4dcb-b4ba-5b9b48748baa&k=70570&p=1|accessdate=2008-02-18|last=Kari|first=Shannon|work=National Post|date=2007-05-24|title=Murder mystery deepens as $25M lawsuit filed}}</ref> In June 2006, Croitoru also pled guilty to the charges of extortion and violating the terms of his bail. As a result, he was forced to forfeit $10,000 of the bail money.<ref name=bail/>

===United Nations gang===
On May 15, 2009, Croitoru was arrested, along with seven other members of the [[United Nations (gang)|United Nations]] gang. They were charged with conspiracy to commit murder for allegedly plotting to kill the [[Bacon Brothers (gangsters)|Bacon Brothers]] and other members of the [[Red Scorpions]] gang.<ref>{{cite web|title=8 alleged UN gang members charged|work=CBC|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/british-columbia/story/2009/05/15/bc-gang-charges-united-nations.html|accessdate=2009-05-15|date=2009-05-15}}</ref><ref name=vsun>{{cite web|title=Eight UN gangsters now charged with conspiracy to murder Bacon brothers|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/news/alleged+gangsters+charged+with+plotting+kill+rivals/1600901/story.html|accessdate=2009-05-15|date=2009-05-15|first=Kim|last=Bolan|work=Vancouver Sun}}</ref> On January 24, 2011, Croituro was charged with first degree murder in connection with the execution of Jonathan Barber <ref>{{cite web|title=Johnny K-9 faces murder charge|url=http://www.thespec.com/news/article/477725--johnny-k-9-faces-murder-charge|accessdate=2011-01-25|date=2011-01-25}}</ref> and the attempted murder of Barber's girlfriend Vicky King, then 17, in [[Burnaby]] on 9 May 2008.<ref name=TorontoStarAugust11>{{cite news|last=Edwards|first=Peter|title=Hamilton wrestler <U+2018>Johnny K-9<U+2019> a member of B.C. gang|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/article/1046565|accessdate=16 October 2011|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=29 August 2011}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Before entering wrestling, Croitoru played [[Junior ice hockey|junior hockey]] for the [[Kitchener Rangers]] in the [[Ontario Hockey League]].<ref name=new/> He was not drafted to the [[National Hockey League]], however, and he decided to pursue professional wrestling instead. Croitoru is an accomplished weightlifter, and he once bench pressed 625 pounds.<ref name=mike/> While awaiting his murder trial, Croitoru ran a home renovation business until he was unable to secure a bank loan to cover business expenses.<ref name=bail/> After closing the business, Croitoru supported himself by working as a used car salesman.<ref name=bail/>

Croitoru currently lives in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]] with his [[Common-law marriage|common-law wife]] and his two young sons.<ref name=new/> He most recently worked as a bodyguard for [[Lion's Gate Entertainment]], providing protection for such actors as [[Jack Nicholson]] and [[Cyndi Lauper]].<ref name=new/><ref name=bail>{{cite web|title=Unruly wrestler must pay crown $10,000|url=http://www.thespec.com/News/Local/article/298436|work=Hamilton Spectator|accessdate=2010-06-14|date=December 19, 2007|last=Legall|first=Paul}}</ref> Croitoru also had a brief acting career, appearing in a movie titled ''Oklahoma Smugglers'', in which he portrayed a wrestler, and such television shows as [[Reaper (TV series)|Reaper]].<ref name=vsun/><ref name=nyt>{{cite web|title=Oklahoma Smugglers (1988): Acting Credits|work=New York Times|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/430876/Oklahoma-Smugglers/cast|accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref>

